@contendentsjzu Dogecoin has entered the real world—and it’s not leaving. 🐶🔥
Even established coins like Dogecoin and Shiba Inu, which once dominated the market, saw significant drops—down 48% and 71% from their all-time highs, respectively, by late 2024.

High-profile endorsements, particularly from Elon Musk, propelled Dogecoin to new heights. Musk’s tweets in 2021, such as calling Dogecoin "the people's crypto," triggered massive price surges, pushing its market cap to over $62 billion at its peak.

The real explosion of meme coins occurred during the 2020-2021 crypto bull market. Fueled by pandemic-era boredom, retail investors on platforms like Reddit and Twitter began pouring money into Dogecoin and its imitators.

Dogecoin was meant to be a joke but quickly gained traction due to its lighthearted community and low entry price.Its early rise was modest, but it laid the groundwork for what would become a broader trend.

The phenomenon began with Dogecoin, launched in December 2013 by software engineers Billy Markus and Jackson Palmer as a parody of the burgeoning crypto market. Inspired by the "Doge" meme featuring a Shiba Inu dog.

In the flickering glow of a thousands screens, the world watched as a single post from a billionaire’s X handle ignited a frenzy—Dogecoin soared to the moon.
